    "rating_count": 520,
    "skill_content": "---\nname: Hashtag Strategist\ndescription: Recommends a tiered hashtag and keyword set sized to account reach, balancing broad, niche, and branded tags while avoiding banned or spammy ones. Use when choosing tags for a post or building a reusable set.\n---\n# Hashtag Strategist\n\nHashtags are a discovery and categorization tool, not a magic reach lever — and on several platforms keyword-rich captions now matter more than tags. The goal is to put a post in front of a reachable, relevant audience, which means matching tag competitiveness to the account's actual size.\n\n## Tier by Reach, Don't Chase Volume\nBuild three tiers. Broad/high-volume (1M+ posts): one or two only — a small account will be buried in seconds, so these are aspirational reach, not the workhorse. Niche/mid (10k-500k posts): the core of the set, specific enough that the post can rank and stay visible. Branded/community (your own + small community tags): always include the brand tag and 1-2 community ones to build a searchable archive. The smaller the account, the more the set should skew niche and small.\n\n## Size the Set to the Platform\nInstagram: 3-8 well-chosen tags outperform the 30-tag dump — relevance beats quantity and the maximum is a ceiling, not a target. TikTok: 3-5 tags mixing one broad discovery tag with specific topical ones; the caption keywords and on-screen text matter as much. LinkedIn: 1-3 only, and they should read naturally. X/Twitter: 1-2 max — more looks spammy and hurts. YouTube: tags plus, more importantly, keyword-rich titles and descriptions.\n\n## Treat Keywords as First-Class\nInstagram, TikTok, and LinkedIn now surface content via caption and on-screen text in search. Recommend the literal search phrases a target viewer would type, woven into the caption naturally — not only hashtags. This is often higher-leverage than the tag list itself.\n\n## Vet Every Tag\nScreen for banned, broken, or shadow-flagged tags (these silently suppress a post) and for tags hijacked by unrelated or spammy content. Avoid tags so generic they're pure noise. Reject follow-for-follow and engagement-pod tags outright — they attract bots and can flag the account.\n\n## Build Rotating Sets, Not One Block\nGive 2-3 interchangeable sets so the account isn't posting an identical tag block every time (which can look automated). Tie each set to a content pillar.\n\n## When Tags Won't Help\nIf the account's problem is content quality or consistency, say so — no hashtag set rescues a post nobody wants to watch. For very small or hyper-niche brands, recommend leaning on keywords and community tags over reach tags entirely."
